###DESCRIPTION
## Determine an exponential model of a bacteria population.
##ENDDESCRIPTION

## DBsubject(Algebra)
## DBchapter(Exponential and logarithmic expressions and functions)
## DBsection(Applications and models - general)
## Date(6/3/2002)
## Institution(Rochester)
## MLT(Bacteria_doublingTimeGiven)
## Level(4)
## TitleText1('College Algebra')
## AuthorText1('Stewart, Redlin, Watson')
## EditionText1('3')
## Section1('6.6')
## Problem1('14')
## KEYWORDS('logarithms,exponentials','exponential growth,decay','Algebra', 'Exponential', 'Logarithmic', 'Applications')
##TYPE('word problem')

DOCUMENT();    # This should be the first executable line in the problem.

loadMacros('PGstandard.pl', 'PGML.pl', 'PGcourse.pl');

Context('Numeric')->variables->are(t => Real);

$p0 = random(80, 200, 10);
$m  = random(30, 150, 60);
$h  = $m / 60;
$b  = random(2, 4);

if ($b == 2) { $s = 'doubles' }
if ($b == 3) { $s = 'triples' }
if ($b == 4) { $s = 'quadruples' }

$P = Formula("$p0 * $b**(t/$h)");

BEGIN_PGML

A certain bacteria population is known to [$s] every [$m] minutes.  Suppose that there are initially [$p0] bacteria.

What is the size of the population after [` t `] hours?   [_]{$P}

END_PGML

BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION
This is an exponential model and since the population [$s], then the base is [$b]. 

Also, since [`t`] is measured in hours, recall that 
[``` [$m]\;\text{min} \cdot \frac{1\;\text{hr}}{60\;\text{hr}} = [$h]\;\text{hours}
```]
This is needed for the exponent of the model:
[``` P(t) = [$P] ```]
END_PGML_SOLUTION

ENDDOCUMENT();
